\section{Housing and households}
\label{sec:personal_action_housing_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Houses and households are the source of both sustainability problems and sustainability opportunities,
as discussed in Chapter~\ref{chap:housing_and_households}.
Homes are a significant piece of infrastructure that
require large amounts of energy and materials to construct and
determine energy use patterns for decades to come.
When choosing a home, people should
buy smaller and used homes rather than
constructing large, new homes.
Used homes avoid the energy and material cost of construction.
Small homes reduce ongoing energy consumption for heating and cooling.
Purchasing a well-insulated home (or retrofitting with improved insulation) reduces
ongoing energy costs for heating and cooling.

At home, people can make decisions to reduce energy and material consumption in their daily lives, too.
Homes should be filled with Energy Star appliances, where possible,
to minimize energy consumption in daily life.
Be especially concerned about energy efficiency when appliances need to be replaced.
The energy cost of manufacturing, transporting, and disposing appliances
often outweighs energy savings from using new appliances.
So replacing low-efficiency devices with high-efficiency devices is almost always beneficial to sustainability.
For example, homeowners should replace all incandescent and compact fluorescent lamps
with LED lamps when replacement is necessary.
And low-efficiency gasoline-powered lawnmowers should be eschewed in favor of
native plantings that need little care.
When needed, reel mowers are preferred to gasoline powered mowers.

As with all energy efficiency measures, the rebound effect should be considered.
Money saved by being more efficient should be used for additional energy efficient appliances
rather than other purchases in the economy (which themselves demand more energy consumption).


